Introduction¶

Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace. Through Prosper, people can invest in each other where borrowers apply online for a fixed-rate, fixed-term loan between $\$2,000$ and $\$40,000$. Individuals and institutions can invest in the loans and earn attractive returns. Prosper handles all loan servicing on behalf of the matched borrowers and investors.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 113937 rows and 81 columns most of which have numerical type data. Other columns have the categorical type data while others have a date-time type data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most focused in getting to know how many investors get to lend loans based on the borrower's occupation, gender, their income range, their employment status, their state of residence, their stated monthly income et cetera.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The ListingKey showing the number of borrowers and the Investors column will help me support my investigation as it will give me a clue on how many investors get to invest based on most of the borrowers information.

# These are functions defined to plot Bar Graphs of Univariate plots using Seaborn's Countplot function.

def bar_texts(var, x, **kwargs):
    prosper = var.value_counts()
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    ax = plt.figure(figsize= (8, 6)).subplots()
    sb.countplot(data= prosper_loan, x= x, y= None, hue= None, color= base_color);
    ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)

    locs, labels  = plt.xticks(rotation= 30)

    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count = prosper[label.get_text()]
        percentage = '{:.2f}%'.format((count * 100) / prosper.sum())
        m = plt.text(loc, count, percentage, ha= 'center', va= 'baseline')
    return m

def barh_texts(var, y, **kwargs):
    prosper = var.value_counts()
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    ax = plt.figure(figsize= (8, 6)).subplots()
    sb.countplot(data= prosper_loan, y= y, color= base_color);
    ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
    
    locs, labels = plt.yticks()
    
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count = prosper[label.get_text()]
        percentage = '{:.2f}%'.format((count * 100) / prosper.sum())
        m = plt.text(count, loc, percentage, va= 'center', ha= 'left')

In [18]:
def sqrt_transform(x, inverse= False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.sqrt(x)
    else:
        return np.power(x, 2)

# A histogram showing the distribution of borrowers Debt to Income Ratio.
bins = np.arange(prosper_loan.DebtToIncomeRatio.min(), sqrt_transform(prosper_loan.DebtToIncomeRatio.max())+0.025, 0.025)
plt.hist(data= prosper_loan, x= 'DebtToIncomeRatio', bins= bins);
plt.xlim(0, 1.2)
ticks = np.linspace(0, 1.2, 12)
plt.xticks(ticks, np.around(sqrt_transform(ticks), 2), rotation= 30)
plt.xlabel('Debt to Income Ratio')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('A graph of debt to income ratio against frequency');

The figure above shows the distibution of debt to income ratio on a squareroot xscale. From the graph, we can see that the distribution is right skewed with a majority of the borrowers having a low debt to income ratio. It is also evident that most investors lend those borrowers money as they are the majority in the group.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most of the data in the dataset had distributions that were skewed to the right and thus I had to perform log transformations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

For the debt to income ratio, I had to do a squareroot transformation since there were values that had a zero and performing a log transformation meant that the minimum values could be up to negative infinity.

For the stated monthly income column, I had to remove the outliers of values that were above $\$50,000$.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

An interesting result in the third multivariate visualization is that a majority of the borrowers borrowed less than $\$30000$ with those who borrowed an original amount $\$30000$ or more all seem to be having a return of a large sum of money in their monthly loan payments with the majority of those borrowers having only one investor lending them loans.

Conclusions¶

The number of investors lending a particular individual or institution loans depends on their ratings, their stated monthly income, their home ownership status, their income range et cetera. A majority of the borrowers had only one investor lending them loans.

The dataset is from a US based peer-to-peer lending marketplace as all borrowers are from states from the US.
